{"cursor":"11043","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Adil Najam image = Adil Najam in 2010.JPG caption = birth_date =\n| birth_place = Rawalpindi, Punjab, Pakistan death_date = death_place =\n| residence = Boston, Massachusetts, USA nationality = Pakistani field =\n| international relations, conflict resolution, and environment and development\n| policy work_institution = Boston University Massachusetts Institute of\n| Technology (MIT) Tufts University Lahore University of Management\n| Sciences (LUMS) alma_mater = University of Engineering and Technology, Lahore,\n| Pakistan Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT), U.S.A known_for =\n| prizes = Sitara-i-Imtiaz (2009) Fletcher School Paddock Teaching Award\n| (2004) MIT's Goodwin Medal for Effective Teaching (1997) Pakistan\n| Television Outstanding Achievement Medal (1990)}}\n\n'Adil Najam' is a Pakistani academic and intellectual, currently the Vice\nChancellor of the Lahore University of Management Sciences (LUMS). He is a\nleading expert on issues related to developing country environmental policy,\nespecially climate change, and also on the politics of South Asia. He was the\nDirector of the Frederick S. Pardee Center for the Study of the Longer-Range\nFuture and Professor of International Relations and of Geography & Environment,\nboth at Boston University before joining as Vice Chancellor of Lahore University\nof Management Sciences (LUMS). He is the winner of\nteaching awards at MIT and the Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy, and the\nauthor of multiple books, scholarly papers and book chapters. He is also the\nfounding editor of the blog [[Pakistaniat|Pakistaniat: All Things Pakistan]] and\na highly sought public speaker.\n","linknr":219,"url":"Adil_Najam","recorded":1364759162,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Adil_Najam&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Adil_Najam&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipe